<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910405-0052</DOCNO><DOCID>910405-0052.</DOCID><HL>   Consumer Group Criticizes   Higher Rates Tied to Loans</HL><DATE>04/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)FORECASTS andamp; ANALYSIS OF U.S. ECONOMIC INDICATORS (EMJ)CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)</IN><NS>ECONOMIC NEWS, TRENDS, INDEXES, PROJECTIONS, ANALYSES (ECO)</NS><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Higher interest rates on personal, auto andcredit card loans are &quot;retarding the nation's economicrecovery,&quot; the Consumer Federation of America charged.   &quot;During a period when consumer savings rates have droppedsharply, credit-card and personal-loan rates have risen, andautomobile loan rates have declined little,&quot; said StephenBrobeck, the group's executive director.</LP><TEXT>   Citing figures complied by Bank Rate Monitor, the groupsaid that average rates paid on six-month certificates ofdeposit fell nearly a third to 6.22% last month from 9.02%from April 1989, and rates banks paid on money marketaccounts fell to 5.45% from 6.42%.   But over that two-year period, the average rate bankscharged on two-year personal loans rose to 17.33% from16.94%, while the average rate on creditcard debt edged up to18.88% from 18.08%. Interest charges on auto loans fell to12.04% from 12.50%.   Over the last six months, the Federal Reserve Board haspushed rates down to fight the recession. Mortgage rates havedeclined 16% over the last two years, but banks have beenslow to reduce other consumer rates. President Bush hascalled for lower interest rates, but the White House, worriedabout strains in the banking system, hasn't pressed bankshard to reduce rates.</TEXT></DOC>